<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-12-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-12-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="115" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d115">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.34537/38.</note>
                        <head>[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-12-11"><hi rend="italic">December 11,
                                    1910</hi></date></dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 502.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: While referring to previous
                            correspondence, and in order that there may be no misunderstanding, I
                            have the honor to inform you that I have not taken up officially in any
                            way with the Cuban Government the question of the enlargement of our
                            naval station at Guantánamo, and the possible renunciation of the Bahía
                            Honda lease. Clippings from La Lucha, which have been sent the
                            Department in the usual way, would appear to indicate that I have
                            already begun, negotiations in the premises.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John B. Jackson.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>